1. UI Interaction & DOM Handling

These are very popular in interviews.

Examples:

Implement Drag and Drop (without libraries)

Create a Sortable List

Build a Modal / Popup with open–close logic

Create a Dropdown that closes on outside click

Implement a Tooltip on hover

Build a Tabs component

What they test:

DOM manipulation

Event handling

State management

Clean JS logic

2. Scrolling & Performance

Very common for real-world apps.

Examples:

Implement Infinite Scroll

Create Lazy Loading images

Detect when user reaches bottom of page

Build a Virtualized List (render only visible items)

Implement Scroll to Top button

What they test:

Scroll events

Performance optimization

API pagination

Debounce / Throttle

3. API & Data Handling

Almost guaranteed in interviews.

Examples:

Fetch data from API and display list

Add Search + Filter

Implement Pagination

Handle Loading / Error / Empty states

Implement Debounce search input

What they test:

Async JS (fetch, async/await)

State updates

Error handling

UX thinking

4. Forms & Validation

Very practical tasks.

Examples:

Build a Login / Signup form

Implement Form Validation

Show inline error messages

Disable submit button until form is valid

Password strength indicator

What they test:

Controlled inputs

Validation logic

User feedback

5. JavaScript Logic Challenges

Often mixed with UI.

Examples:

Implement Debounce / Throttle

Create a Todo App

Implement Undo / Redo

Build a Timer / Countdown

Create a Carousel / Slider

What they test:

Core JavaScript

Closures

State logic

6. CSS & Layout Tasks

Especially for frontend roles.

Examples:

Create a Responsive Layout

Center a div (multiple ways)

Build a Sticky Header

Implement Dark / Light Mode

CSS Grid / Flexbox layout

What they test:

CSS fundamentals

Responsiveness

Real-world layout skills

7. React-Specific Practical Tasks (if React role)

Very common now.

Examples:

Build Infinite Scroll in React

Drag and Drop using React state

Create reusable components

Use useEffect for API calls

Optimize with useMemo / useCallback